column1: Before 1 October 2019, will the OSCE verify that separatist forces have withdrawn all of their heavy weaponry in accordance with the Minsk II Peace Agreement?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: For the specific heavy weaponry withdrawal requirements see Annex 1, No. 2 of the Minsk II Agreement. The OSCE has established a Special Monitoring Mission in Ukraine and one of its tasks is monitoring Minsk II compliance (Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe, Reuters). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

As it stands right now, Eastern Ukrainian separatists serve as a very important bargaining chip for Russia in its proxy conflict with Ukraine. In order to legitimize the separatist factions to as great an extent as possible, it's necessary for Russia to keep them equipped and at a parity with regional Ukrainian security forces. Neither side has a definitive upper hand in the conflict, and while skirmishes are still occurring (in violation of the supposed ceasefire) neither side has an incentive to deescalate their forces and thus present a potential weakness to the enemy.

Forecast: Assess a 4% probability that OSCE will verify that all heavy weapons are withdrawn per Minsk II. The bar set by Minsk II is extremely high with the requirement to remove all heavy machine guns, artillery, and missile systems. The monitoring organization OSCE has not had one day in the last year without some type of violation. The small chance of meeting this high bar hinges on a watershed influence by Russia where they influence a full separatist forces pull out, to include all heavy weapons. Definitions – 1. Minsk II Peace Agreement - “Withdrawal of all heavy weapons by both sides by equal distances in order to create a security zone of at least 50 km wide from each other” and “Withdrawal of all foreign armed formations, military equipment, as well as mercenaries from the territory of Ukraine under monitoring of the OSCE.” 2. OSCE and Special Monitoring Mission to Ukraine (SMM) – established to monitor and report status of all UNSCR and agreements within OSCE scope. Key Facts: 1. Between 25 February and 10 March, the SMM recorded almost 15,700 ceasefire violations (compared with over 23,000 in the previous two-week period). The Mission also observed 90 weapons in violation of the agreed withdrawal lines (62 in areas not con-trolled by the Government). reports shown below in the key facts. They are the verifier in this case, and they don’t register one day without a violation of Minsk II.

There is little to no possibility of such drastic changes happening. This is because the Kremlin is interested in keeping a frozen conflict in Ukraine and therefore will be a major player. However, Zaharchenko's death showed that not all separatists are Putin's puppets. It is clear that some of them regard Putin as a savior but some also view him with contempt because he failed to secure many social guarantees that he promised to Donbass. Therefore, analyzing Kremlin's intentions for the region is not enough to make this forecast. However, it is important to also not overestimate the agency of the separatists. There is also a small possibility of some backdoor deal with Ukraine on the part of separatists too that seems too far-fetched as well.

I do not believe that the OSCE will make this declaration. The Kremlin wants to maintain a protracted conflict, and the OSCE wants to keep the SMM alive and funded. Barring any major developments I do not foresee many changes on the ground.

Intuition base rate: 90% chance that a party follows international treaties in a crisis situation. This seems to fit with a paper from the CIIA in 2006 ("the vast majority of treaties―and hundreds of new ones are negotiated each year―do actually work") [1]. According to the paper, it helps if verification is strong (which seems to be the case with Minsk II), sanctions are in place to deter defection (haven't seen something like that on the German Wiki page about Minsk II) and one deals with cooperative countries (separatists and Russia sound a bit defective to me).

The SMM observed weapons that could not be verified as withdrawn, as their storage did not comply with the criteria set out in the 16 October 2015 notification from the SMM to the signatories of the Package of Measures on effective monitoring and verification of the withdrawal of heavy weapons. In government-controlled areas of Donetsk region, the SMM noted that 20 self-propelled howitzers (18 2S1 and two 2S3 Akatsiya, 152mm) were still missing.

The OSCE is one of many international organizations which have lost credibility, since until now it has shown a blind eye on the atrocities the Ukrainian fascistic junta is doing in so called separatists areas. There live Ukrainians, who have not accepted the ousting of the legally elected president, which was possible only with the help of USA. The main contributing factor to the loss of trust to those international organizations is the behavior of the USA - its is obeying to decisions of the international organizations only, if it fits it's national interests. If i.e. the UN does what the US wants - that's good, if not, USA doesn't care and does any way what it wants. This behavior shatters the international system of institutions, which was designed after uncounted wars to solve the various conflicts on the base of law and negotiations - a system, which grants protection for small countries, a system which was designed to prevent big and strong countries to solve their problems at the cost of weaker nations. The second problem is, that US has taken control of international institutions, which were set up to function as independent specialized international bodies, who will be trusted from all nations, independently of their conflicts among each other. There are many examples - like the OPCW, Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, and other, like the anti doping organization. In a highly politicized conflict against Russia the USA lead "West" countries have manipulated the results of the above mentioned bodies and have done a tremendous damage to the very foundation of the modern globalized world. This has triggered an earthquake for the international relations, which will settle only then, when new rules of engagement will be established. Those are either the reestablishment of the trust in the integrity of those international institutions, or the rule of the stronger. Needless to say, which would be the better one - therefore the question: Is the current US administration destroying the existing international system only, to gain some short sighted advantage in a tactical battle? Obviously, the development of the multi polar world is unavoidable. It can be merely postponed for some time for the price of destructing the above mentioned system and increasing tensions among nuclear powers - is this a wise political behavior? I am doubting it.
